<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is inductance?", answer: "Inductance is the property of an electrical conductor that opposes changes in current, measured in henrys (H). When current through an inductor changes, it generates a voltage (back-EMF) proportional to the rate of change: V = L * dI/dt. Inductance depends on the coil geometry — more turns, larger area, and a magnetic core all increase inductance. Practical inductors range from nanohenrys in high-frequency circuits to several henrys in power supplies." },
  { question: "How much energy does an inductor store?", answer: "An inductor stores energy in its magnetic field: E = 1/2 * L * I^2, where L is inductance in henrys and I is current in amperes. Unlike capacitors which store energy in an electric field, inductors store energy magnetically. The energy is released when current decreases. This is why disconnecting an inductor suddenly can produce a large voltage spike — the stored energy must go somewhere. Flyback converters and boost converters exploit this energy storage mechanism." },
  { question: "How do inductors combine in series and parallel?", answer: "In series (assuming no mutual coupling), inductances add: Lt = L1 + L2 + L3 + ... In parallel, the reciprocals add: 1/Lt = 1/L1 + 1/L2 + 1/L3 + ... This is the same behavior as resistors: series adds, parallel gives a smaller total. The total parallel inductance is always less than the smallest individual inductor. Mutual inductance between coils can modify these formulas, but for well-separated inductors, the simple formulas apply." },
  { question: "What is the RL time constant?", answer: "The RL time constant tau = L/R determines how quickly current changes in an inductor-resistor circuit. After one time constant, current reaches about 63.2% of its final value. After three time constants, it reaches about 95%, and after five, about 99.3%. The time constant is important for designing filters, switching power supplies, and relay circuits. A large inductance or small resistance gives a longer time constant (slower current changes)." },
  { question: "What are common inductor applications?", answer: "Inductors are used in power supplies (energy storage in switching converters, filtering), radio frequency circuits (tuning with capacitors to select frequencies), transformers (mutual inductance between coupled coils), motors and generators (electromagnetic energy conversion), chokes (blocking high-frequency noise while passing DC), and electromagnetic interference filters. Every switching power supply in modern electronics contains inductors." }
]) %>

